        <p>Your Sept. 5 editorial about the technology gender gap cited the lack of encouragement in school as a major reason that too few women enter the field. This is surely the case, but the gender pay gap in technology employment also deserves mention.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Sept. 5 editorial about the technology gender gap cited the lack of encouragement in school as a major reason that too few women enter the field. This is surely the case, but the gender pay gap in technology employment also deserves mention.</p>
        <p>A recent study by the President's Council of Economic Advisers found that even after controlling for education and age differences, women are paid 17 percent less than men in information technology jobs. Part of this gap stems from the fact that women end up in lower paying occupations within the information technology sector, and part stems from gender discrimination.</p>
        <p>Along with educational reforms, taking aim at the pay gap should help reduce the gender gap in the technology field.</p>
        <p>JARED BERNSTEIN  Washington, Sept. 6, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an economist at the Economic Policy Institute.</p>
      </block>
